SIMPLE: ordinary
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Ordinary
<hw>Or"di*na*ry</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>ordinarius</ets>, fr. <ets>ordo</ets>, <ets>ordinis</ets>, order:
cf. F. <ets>ordinaire</ets>. See <er>Order</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>According to established order; methodical; settled; regular.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧The <xex>ordinary</xex> forms of law.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Addison.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Common; customary; usual.</def>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Method is not less requisite in <qex>ordinary</qex> conversation
that in writing.</q> <rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Of common rank, quality, or ability; not
distinguished by superior excellence or beauty; hence, not distinguished
in any way; commonplace; inferior; of little merit; <as>as, men of
<ex>ordinary</ex> judgment; an <ex>ordinary</ex> book.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>An <qex>ordinary</qex> lad would have acquired little or no useful
knowledge in such a way.</q> <rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Ordinary seaman</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>one not
expert or fully skilled, and hence ranking below an <contr>able
seaman</contr>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Normal; common; usual; customary.</syn> <usage>
See <er>Normal</er>. -- <er>Ordinary</er>, <er>Common</er>. A thing is
<xex>common</xex> in which many persons share or partake; as, a
<xex>common</xex> practice. A thing is <xex>ordinary</xex> when it is
apt to come round in the regular common order or succession of
events.</usage>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ordinary</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Ordinary
<hw>Or"di*na*ry</hw>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Ordinaries</plw> <pr>(-r⟦icr⟧z)</pr>.</plu> <sn>1.</sn>
<fld>(Law)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <fld>(Roman Law)</fld> <def>An officer who
has original jurisdiction in his own right, and not by deputation.</def>
<sd>(b)</sd> <fld>(Eng. Law)</fld> <def>One who has immediate
jurisdiction in matters ecclesiastical; an ecclesiastical judge; also, a
deputy of the bishop, or a clergyman appointed to perform divine service
for condemned criminals and assist in preparing them for death.</def>
<sd>(c)</sd> <fld>(Am. Law)</fld> <def>A judicial officer, having
generally the powers of a judge of probate or a surrogate.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The mass; the common run.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I see no more in you than in the <qex>ordinary</qex>⟦br⟧
Of nature's salework.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>That which is so common, or continued, as to be
considered a settled establishment or institution.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Spain had no other wars save those which were grown into an
<qex>ordinary</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Anything which is in ordinary or common
use.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Water buckets, wagons, cart wheels, plow socks, and other
<qex>ordinaries</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W. Scott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>A dining room or eating house where a meal is
prepared for all comers, at a fixed price for the meal, in distinction
from one where each dish is separately charged; a table d'h⟦ocir⟧te;
hence, also, the meal furnished at such a dining room.</def>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>All the odd words they have picked up in a coffeehouse, or a
gaming <qex>ordinary</qex>, are produced as flowers of style.</q>
<rj><qau>Swift.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He exacted a tribute for licenses to hawkers and peddlers and to
<qex>ordinaries</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Bancroft.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Her.)</fld> <def>A charge or bearing of simple
form, one of nine or ten which are in constant use. The
<stype>bend</stype>, <stype>chevron</stype>, <stype>chief</stype>,
<stype>cross</stype>, <stype>fesse</stype>, <stype>pale</stype>, and
<stype>saltire</stype> are uniformly admitted as ordinaries. Some
authorities include <xex>bar</xex>, <xex>bend sinister</xex>,
<xex>pile</xex>, and others. See <er>Subordinary</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>In ordinary</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>In actual and
constant service; statedly attending and serving; <as>as, a physician or
chaplain <ex>in ordinary</ex>. An ambassador <ex>in ordinary</ex> is one
constantly resident at a foreign court</as>.</cd> <sd>(b)</sd>
<fld>(Naut.)</fld> <cd>Out of commission and laid up; -- said of a naval
vessel.</cd> -- <col><b>Ordinary of the Mass</b></col> <fld>(R. C.
Ch.)</fld>, <cd>the part of the Mass which is the same every day; --
called also the <altname>canon of the Mass</altname>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ordinaryship</ent>⟦br⟧
